</tbody></table><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p><b style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">&nbsp;Short Description</b></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">In order to serve multiple connections, Xpl module creates a
connection pool. Internally the connection pool is implemented using a socket
set and this socket set is served by a set of thread. This set of threads
serving the set of sockets is configured using the variable
MAX_SOCKETSET_THREADS. <o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Long Description</b><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">By default the socket sets contains&nbsp; 60 sockets&nbsp;
and 6 threads serves them. In large environments with more connections ,
keeping the&nbsp; socket set smaller is more
efficient. <o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">













</p><p class="MsoNormal">For example in an environment with the default socket set ie
60 and served by 6 threads(1:10), even if&nbsp;
59 connections are closed whole socket set is active in the memory.&nbsp; In such scenarios if the number of threads is
3 and the socket set is 10(1:3), the number of threads are thrice the number
sockets;&nbsp; as result requests gets
processed faster and a faster release of the socket set. Due to this very
reason in large environments where the number of connections are very high
keeping the value of&nbsp;
SOCKETS_PER_SOCKETSET to 10 and&nbsp;
MAX_SOCKETSET_THREADS to 3 makes is recommended.</p><h2 style="margin: 0.25in 0in 12pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;"><a name="_Toc491176823"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="mso-ansi-font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;
