  </td>
 </tr>
</tbody></table><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="font-size: 13pt; line-height: 107%; color: rgb(46, 116, 181);"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></span><b style="font-size: medium; color: windowtext; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">Short
Description</b></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">Name
resolution happens primarily from host to IP address and in the reverse look
up, resolution takes place from IP address to hostname.&nbsp; The DISABLE_DNS variable is used to control
the reverse lookups happening inside the application during communication.
Setting this variable to true prevents the reverse lookup calls on the system
for the specified target.<o:p></o:p></font></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3"><b>Long
Description</b><o:p></o:p></font></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">Xpl library
provides mechanism to lookup the hostname from the IP address. This is called
reverse lookup and in products consuming LCORE api-s, it is enabled by setting
DISABLE_DNS to false. In most of the scenarios reverse lookup may not be
necessary and hence the reverse lookup is disabled by default. <o:p></o:p></font></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">There might
be certain scenarios where reverse lookup might be necessary. <o:p></o:p></font></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"></p><ul><li><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">Multi
NIC systems where different IPs map to different Hostnames, If there are
discrepancies with the hostname associated with the interface is getting
reflected in the application enable the reverse lookup by setting DISABLE_DNS
to false.</font></span></span></li><li><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">PROXY
configuration and CLIs.&nbsp; Certain CLIs
like bbcutil gettarget can take an IP or Hostname. In case an IP is passed,
the PROXY variable is directly checked for the target if DISABLE_DNS is set to
true. In case where reverse lookup is configured, </font></span></span></li><li><span class="LabelChar"><span style="line-height: 107%; color: windowtext;"><font size="3">In
certain systems where message delay is observed due to multiple lookups, check
whether DISABLE_DNS is false and if it is evaluate whether the variable can be
set to true. Ie disable the reverse lookup.</font></span></span>&nbsp;</li></ul><p class="MsoNormal">





















</p><h2><span style="font-weight: normal;"><font size="3">&nbsp;</font><o:p></o:p><a name="_Toc491176828" style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;"><span class="LabelChar"><span style="font-size:13.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;line-height:107%;mso-ascii-font-family:
&quot;Calibri Light&quot;;mso-ascii-theme-font:major-latin;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;
mso-fareast-theme-font:major-fareast;mso-hansi-font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;;
mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin;mso-bidi-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;
mso-bidi-theme-font:major-bidi;color:#2E74B5;mso-themecolor:accent1;mso-themeshade:
191">PROCESS TIMOUT</span></span></a></span></h2>

<table class="MsoTableGrid" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="0" style="border-left: none;">
